    <statement>
      <p>
        Fill in the missing values in the table below, given that
        <m>dy/dt = -0.5 y</m>.
        Assume the rate of growth, given by <m>dy/dt</m>, is
        approximately constant over each unit time interval.
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>t</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        \hline
        <m>y</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        Keep in mind the following two precepts to guide your thinking:

        <ol type="i">
          <li>
            <p>
              You are writing down a <em>differential equation</em>, not a
              formula for the quantity of interest.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The net rate of change of the quantity may be easily expressed
              as a difference of the form:
              <m>\mathbf{\text{ rate } _{\text{ in } } - \text{ rate } _{\text{ out } }}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A population of insects grows at a rate proportional to the size of the population.
        Write a differential equation for the size of the population,
        <m>P</m>,
        as a function of time, <m>t</m>.
        Is the constant of proportionality positive or negative?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Radioactive substances decay at a rate proportional to the
        amount of the substance that is present.
        Write a differential equation
        for the quantity, <m>Q</m>,
        of a radioactive substance present at time <m>t</m>.
        (It would make sense to measure <m>Q</m> in either grams or number of atoms.)
        Is the constant of proportionality positive or negative?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A person consumes 10 micrograms (<m>\lt quantity>\lt mag>1\lt /mag>\lt unit prefix="micro" base="gram"/>\lt /quantity> =
        \SI[scientific-notation=true]{0.000001}{g}</m>) a day of toxin.
        This toxin is ingested
        throughout the day.
        It leaves the body at a continuous rate of
        <quantity><mag>3</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity>
        every day.
        Write a differential equation for the amount
        of toxin, <m>A</m>, in micrograms,
        in the person's body as a function of
        the number of days, <m>t</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <sidebyside>

    <exercise workspace="20%">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Is <m>y = 4e^{-8x}</m> a solution of <m>y' + 8y = 0</m>?
          Is <m>y = -4t^2</m> a solution?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>P = Ce^{kt}</m> is a solution of the differential equation <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = -0.02 P</m>.
        </p>

        <task workspace="30%">
          What (if anything) does this tell you about the values of <m>C</m> and <m>k</m>?
        </task>

        <task workspace="20%">
          What must <m>C</m> and <m>k</m> be if <m>P = C e^{kt}</m> also satisfies the condition <m>P = 8</m> when <m>t = 0</m>?
        </task>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  </sidebyside>
</worksheet>

